         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">4/4/96. ¶  ¶ Among the plants, just received from you, dear Mr Tyson, is N. 1 an Acacia in abnormal (monstrous) flowering state, — the plant found by your brother ¶  on the stony Hills. I am glad, tha...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">96.04.04a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Isaac Tyson</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">MS 58 (044) MUE, WA Herbarium, Perth.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">4/4/96.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Among the plants, just received from you, dear Mr Tyson, is N. 1 an Acacia in abnormal (monstrous) flowering state, — the plant found by your brother<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Probably William Tyson, who jointly owned the pastoral lease of Mount Narryer station, WA, with Isaac Tyson. Another brother, John Tyson, is a less likely possibility.</p>
               </note> on the stony Hills. I am glad, that he also keeps his eyes upon uncommon plant. Kindly ask him to <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">pick</hi>
               </seg> up <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">all</hi>
               </seg> sorts of very <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">minute</hi>
               </seg> plants this season for me. I like him also to send a sample of <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">any herb</hi>
               </seg> (not only grass), on which Herds and flocks feed with avidity there, and to mark it as such.</p>
            <table n="Table1">
               <row>
                  <cell style="padding-left: 0.0556in; padding-right: 0.0556in; padding-top: 0in; padding-bottom: 0in; border: none; ">
                     <p rend="letter"
                        style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">8,</p>
                  </cell>
                  <cell style="padding-left: 0.0556in; padding-right: 0.0556in; padding-top: 0in; padding-bottom: 0in; border: none; ">
                     <p rend="letter"
                        style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <name key="Bulbine%20semibarbata">Bulbine semibarbata</name> Haworth This likely could be traced northward to within the circle of capricorn, if any one on the great pastures just within the tropics could be induced to collect</p>
                  </cell>
               </row>
               <row>
                  <cell style="padding-left: 0.0556in; padding-right: 0.0556in; padding-top: 0in; padding-bottom: 0in; border: none; ">
                     <p rend="letter"
                        style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">6</p>
                  </cell>
                  <cell style="padding-left: 0.0556in; padding-right: 0.0556in; padding-top: 0in; padding-bottom: 0in; border: none; ">
                     <p rend="letter"
                        style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <name key="Dianella">Dianella</name>
                     </p>
                     <p rend="letter"
                        style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">but flowers and fruits absent</p>
                  </cell>
               </row>
               <row>
                  <cell style="padding-left: 0.0556in; padding-right: 0.0556in; padding-top: 0in; padding-bottom: 0in; border: none; ">
                     <p rend="letter"
                        style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">2</p>
                  </cell>
                  <cell style="padding-left: 0.0556in; padding-right: 0.0556in; padding-top: 0in; padding-bottom: 0in; border: none; ">
                     <p rend="letter"
                        style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <name key="Candollea">Candollea</name>
                     </p>
                     <p rend="letter"
                        style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">Perhaps new. As I have only one flower on the specimen sent, could you let me have your<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                           <p rend="Footnote"
                              style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                              xml:lang="en">yours?</p>
                        </note> on loan?</p>
                  </cell>
               </row>
               <row>
                  <cell style="padding-left: 0.0556in; padding-right: 0.0556in; padding-top: 0in; padding-bottom: 0in; border: none; ">
                     <p rend="letter"
                        style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">3</p>
                  </cell>
                  <cell style="padding-left: 0.0556in; padding-right: 0.0556in; padding-top: 0in; padding-bottom: 0in; border: none; ">
                     <p rend="letter"
                        style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <name key="Ptilotus%20parvifolius">Ptilotus parvifolius</name> FvM.</p>
                     <p rend="letter"
                        style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">A rare species only twice found before. The Ptilotus from the hills is very different but without leaves. I like particularly to get notes on any plants horses, cattle or sheep will feed on, as growing on <seg style="">
                           <hi rend="underline">saline flats</hi>
                        </seg>, as the number of really good pasture plants on salty ground is very limited.</p>
                  </cell>
               </row>
               <row>
                  <cell style="padding-left: 0.0556in; padding-right: 0.0556in; padding-top: 0in; padding-bottom: 0in; border: none; ">
                     <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
                  </cell>
                  <cell style="padding-left: 0.0556in; padding-right: 0.0556in; padding-top: 0in; padding-bottom: 0in; border: none; ">
                     <p rend="letter"
                        style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <name key="Brachychiton%20Gregorii">Brachychiton Gregorii</name> FvM</p>
                     <p rend="letter"
                        style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">This is the tree with deeply 3-lobed leaves. Could more seeds be obtained?</p>
                  </cell>
               </row>
               <row>
                  <cell style="padding-left: 0.0556in; padding-right: 0.0556in; padding-top: 0in; padding-bottom: 0in; border: none; ">
                     <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
                  </cell>
                  <cell style="padding-left: 0.0556in; padding-right: 0.0556in; padding-top: 0in; padding-bottom: 0in; border: none; ">
                     <p rend="letter"
                        style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">The Acacia, which yields gum there is A. Sentis, FvM</p>
                  </cell>
               </row>
               <row>
                  <cell style="padding-left: 0.0556in; padding-right: 0.0556in; padding-top: 0in; padding-bottom: 0in; border: none; ">
                     <p rend="letter"
                        style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">5,</p>
                  </cell>
                  <cell style="padding-left: 0.0556in; padding-right: 0.0556in; padding-top: 0in; padding-bottom: 0in; border: none; ">
                     <p rend="letter"
                        style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">I do not remember to have seen this Salt-Bush before Is it tall. I will examine it carefully and if new will name it in honor of you. The specimens however seem not in ripe fruit<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                           <p rend="Footnote"
                              style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                              xml:lang="en">Tyson did not use a single collecting number sequence, and of his two specimens at MEL dated 1896 numbered 5, only MEL 608218 is a salt bush, <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Atriplex amnicola</seg>, described by Wilson &amp; George in 1994; other authors earlier in the 20th century had referred specimens to M's <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Atriplex rhagodioides</seg>.</p>
                        </note>
                     </p>
                  </cell>
               </row>
               <row>
                  <cell style="padding-left: 0.0556in; padding-right: 0.0556in; padding-top: 0in; padding-bottom: 0in; border: none; ">
                     <p rend="letter"
                        style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">4</p>
                  </cell>
                  <cell style="padding-left: 0.0556in; padding-right: 0.0556in; padding-top: 0in; padding-bottom: 0in; border: none; ">
                     <p rend="letter"
                        style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <name key="Ptilotus%20divaricatus">Ptilotus divaricatus</name>, FvM</p>
                  </cell>
               </row>
            </table>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Can you give me the adress of any one likely to pick up plants for me just within or near Capricorn?</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Perhaps <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">you</hi>
               </seg> would, to save time, write to someone for me just within the tropics</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Acacia%20Sentis">Acacia Sentis</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Brachychiton%20Gregorii">Brachychiton Gregorii</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Bulbine%20semibarbata">Bulbine semibarbata</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Candollea">Candollea</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Dianella">Dianella</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Ptilotus%20divaricatus">Ptilotus divaricatus</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Ptilotus%20parvifolius">Ptilotus parvifolius</name>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
         </div>
      </body>
